---
import CaseStudyLayout from "../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro";
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import { uxBanner as UXBanner } from "../utils/images";

const sidebarItems = [
  { text: "Overview", href: "#overview" },
  { text: "Origin Story", href: "#origin" },
  { text: "Key Features", href: "#features" },
  { text: "Technical Stack", href: "#stack" },
  { text: "Challenges", href: "#challenges" },
  { text: "Roadmap", href: "#roadmap" },
  { text: "Retrospective", href: "#retrospective" },
];
---

<CaseStudyLayout
  title="Kingdra Pokemon Teambuilder"
  subtitle="Full-Stack Pokemon Teambuilder - June 2024"
  pageTitle="Kingdra Pokemon Teambuilder - Liam Sullivan"
  sidebarItems={sidebarItems}
  projectRole={[
    "Software Engineering",
    "Product Design",
    "Full-Stack Development",
  ]}
  team={["Solo"]}
  tools={[
    "Next.js",
    "TypeScript",
    "Tailwind",
    "React",
    "GraphQL",
    "MongoDB",
    "Clerk",
    "Apollo Client",
    "Vitest",
  ]}
  timeline={["Ongoing"]}
  githubLink="https://github.com/liambsulliva/pokemon-teambuilder"
  demoLink="https://pokedraft.liambsullivan.com"
  sidebarClassName="fixed right-[calc((100vw-1150px)/2-7rem)] top-56 w-[1350px]"
  isCaseStudy={false}
>
  <Image
    src={UXBanner}
    alt="Kingdra Teambuilder"
    class="mx-auto max-h-[700px] w-auto"
    loading="eager"
    slot="hero"
  />

  <div class="case-study-layout">
    <section class="fade-in pb-10 pt-10 md:flex md:gap-20" id="overview">
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">Overview</h3>
      <div>
        <p>
          Kingdra Pokemon Teambuilder is a full-stack web application I built to
          solve a problem I encountered while organizing a Pokemon draft league
          for my friends. What started as a simple tool for managing draft teams
          evolved into a comprehensive teambuilder that bridges the gap between
          casual and competitive Pokemon team creation.
        </p>
        <br />
        <p>
          The project addresses a critical gap in the Pokemon teambuilder
          market: most existing tools have poor UIs and lack the ability to set
          moves and stats unless you're using Pokemon Showdown. Additionally,
          there's a lack of tools that can create both casual and competitive
          teams in the same place. This application adapts to user preferences,
          allowing seamless switching between game modes.
        </p>
        <br />
        <p>
          Built with Next.js, TypeScript, and a modern tech stack, the
          application features infinite scrolling, real-time stat calculations,
          user authentication, team management, and full import/export
          capabilities with Pokemon Showdown.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="origin" class="fade-in flex gap-8 max-lg:flex-col">
      <div class="">
        <h3 class="!mb-3 text-2xl font-semibold text-white">Origin Story</h3>
        <p>
          The project began in June 2024 as a learning exercise. I wanted to
          master <a
            class="text-link"
            href="https://nextjs.org/"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noreferrer">Next.js</a
          > and build my first real full-stack application. The initial goal was
          simple: create a tool for managing teams in a Pokemon draft league (think
          fantasy football, but with Pokemon).
        </p>
        <br />
        <p>
          However, as I started building, I realized that existing Pokemon
          teambuilders had significant limitations. Most had terrible UIs, and
          few allowed you to actually set moves and stats unless you were using <a
            class="text-link"
            href="https://play.pokemonshowdown.com/"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noreferrer">Pokemon Showdown</a
          >. More importantly, there was no tool that could seamlessly handle
          both casual and competitive team building in the same interface.
        </p>
        <br />
        <p>
          This realization transformed the project from a simple draft tool into
          a comprehensive teambuilder. I spent countless hours implementing the
          core logic, including stat calculations that <a
            class="text-link"
            href="https://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/Stat#Determination_of_stats"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noreferrer">mimic the exact math</a
          > used in the core Pokemon games, integrating with external APIs for Pokemon
          data, and building a robust database schema for team management.
        </p>
        <br />
        <p>
          The project became an exploration of full-stack development, learning
          GraphQL, implementing authentication with Clerk, managing state with
          Apollo Client, and creating a responsive UI that works across devices.
          What started as a learning project became a tool I'm genuinely proud
          of and continue to improve.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

